---
/**
 * /sandboxing/ — Deep dive on Pillar 03: Sandboxing.
 *
 * Audience: a reader who has used Docker, knows "containers are isolated,"
 * but isn't sure what isolation means inside a TEE or what the limits are.
 * This page explains the wasmtime-style fuel-limited execution, the default-
 * DENY network policy, ephemeral storage, and the resource caps.
 */
import PillarLayout from '~/layouts/PillarLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.endsWith('/') ? import.meta.env.BASE_URL : `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`;
---

<PillarLayout
  pillarNumber="03"
  pillarName="Sandboxing"
  title="Sandboxing — What runs inside the enclave, and what it can do"
  description="A deep dive on the execution environment inside the VerdantForged broker: fuel-limited WASM execution, default-DENY network policy, ephemeral storage, and the resource caps that bound every job."
  problem={{
    heading: 'A container is not a sandbox.',
    body: 'Containers share a kernel with the host. If the kernel is compromised, every container is compromised. Even with a perfectly secure kernel, a container can read files it should not, make network calls it should not, run for as long as it likes, and consume all the memory on the host. The blast radius of a bug or a malicious payload is the entire host.',
    analogy: 'A container is a desk in an open-plan office. You can ask people to keep their voices down and not look at your papers, but the office is one room. A broker sandbox is a locked room with a one-way mirror, a timer, a network cable that goes nowhere, and a shredder that runs every time you leave.',
    withoutBroker: 'A malicious or buggy skill can read the host filesystem, make outbound network calls to anywhere, consume all RAM and CPU, and run forever. Even if the skill is well-behaved, a kernel-level bug breaks the isolation for every skill at once.',
  }}
  howItWorks={{
    heading: 'The broker\'s sandbox, in three layers.',
    steps: [
      {
        n: '01',
        title: 'The skill runs inside the attested worker VM.',
        body: 'When the worker boots, the only thing that runs is the minimal skill runtime, inside an SEV-SNP-attested m6a.xlarge EC2. The skill never has access to the host kernel, the host filesystem, or any other process. The host OS — even if compromised — cannot read the skill\'s memory or tamper with its execution. Network egress is gated by an OpenShell policy that drops everything except the broker API.',
      },
      {
        n: '02',
        title: 'Network egress is default-DENY. The only allowed destination is the broker.',
        body: 'The worker boots with an OpenShell-style policy that drops all outbound traffic by default. The only allowed destinations are the broker\'s API (for fetching job envelopes and uploading result blobs) and the broker\'s LLM proxy endpoint (for prompt-template skills routed through the NemoClaw sandbox). A skill cannot phone home or call an attacker\'s server.',
      },
      {
        n: '03',
        title: 'Resource caps are enforced by the runtime, measured into the attestation.',
        body: 'Every job has hard limits: fuel (manifest-declared up to 10⁹, typical ≤ 10⁸), wall-clock (default 30s, manifest-overridable), per-file output ≤ 50 MiB, total output ≤ 100 MiB, memory cap from the manifest. wasmtime kills the skill if it tries to exceed any of these; fuel and epoch interruption are both configured at engine construction. The actual values used are part of the signed result envelope, so the requester can verify the skill did not exceed what was agreed.',
      },
    ],
  }}
  whatStopsWhat={[
    { attack: 'Skill runs forever (denial of service)',      fix: 'wasmtime fuel (≤10⁹) + epoch-interruption wall-clock cap (default 30s, manifest-overridable)' },
    { attack: 'Skill exfiltrates data to an attacker',       fix: 'Default-DENY OpenShell policy; egress only to broker API and broker LLM proxy' },
    { attack: 'Skill tampers with its own WASM binary',      fix: 'Worker recomputes SHA-256 of the on-disk binary against envelope.skill_hash before wasmtime starts; mismatch is refused' },
    { attack: 'Skill overflows the output buffer',           fix: 'Per-file ≤ 50 MiB + total output ≤ 100 MiB, enforced before S3 upload (KMS-encrypted, 24h lifecycle)' },
    { attack: 'Skill persists state between jobs',           fix: 'Worker is ephemeral (or warm-pool with no per-job persistence); EFS envelopes fetched and deleted per-job' },
    { attack: 'Skill consumes all host memory',              fix: 'wasmtime Store memory limit from manifest.declared max_memory_mb' },
    { attack: 'Two skills see each other\'s data',           fix: 'Worker boots a fresh sandbox per dispatch; EFS inbox/outbox paths are job-id-scoped' },
  ]}
  lookAtTheCode={[
    {
      label: 'Resource limit enforcement',
      detail: 'The live broker\'s `validate_submit` checks encrypted_skill / encrypted_data / stripe_pi_id / result_pubkey shape. For file jobs, an X25519 result_pubkey is required (file_encryption_required). Per-skill resource caps come from the registered WASM manifest (max_fuel, max_duration_ms, max_memory_mb).',
      href: '/docs',
    },
    {
      label: 'The fuel meter',
      detail: 'wasmtime counts every instruction the WASM module executes. The fuel_used field in the signed result envelope is the value at completion — the requester can verify the skill did not exceed the manifest\'s max_fuel.',
    },
    {
      label: 'Sandbox limits in the manifest',
      detail: 'Every skill declares its max_fuel, max_duration_ms, and max_memory_mb in the registration request. The broker stores these and pins them at execution time. /v1/skills lets you list and inspect.',
      href: `${base}docs#register-skill`,
    },
  ]}
  next={{ number: '04', name: 'Payment', href: `${base}payment/` }}
/>
